 In programming, an array is a data structure that can store a collection of elements, all of the same data type, in contiguous memory locations. You can think of an array as a single variable that can hold multiple values. Each individual value in an array is called an element.

Arrays are commonly used to store lists or collections of data, such as numbers, strings, or structures. Accessing the elements of an array is typically done using an index. This allows you to access the elements in a specific order, and you can use the same index to modify or retrieve the value of elements.

For example, if you have an array of 5 integers, you might initially set the values as follows:

```java
int[] numbers = new int[5];
numbers[0] = 10;
numbers[1] = 20;
numbers[2] = 30;
numbers[3] = 40;
numbers[4] = 50;
```

In this example, the variable `numbers` is an integer array with a length of 5. Each number in the array is stored at a memory location that is adjacent to the next number in the array. To access elements in this array, you use the index, which starts at 0.

You can use arrays in different programming languages, such as C, Java, Python, and many others. The syntax and capabilities might differ slightly depending on the specific language, but the underlying concept is the same - an array is a data structure that can store a collection of elements of the same type, with each element having a specific position in memory.
